To play BINGO, someone names numbers, chosen at random, and players mark those numbers on their cards.  A player wins when he marks 5 in a row, horizontally, vertically, or diagonally.

How many distinct possibilities are there for the values in the diagonal going from top left to bottom right of a BINGO card, in order?

ground_truth.solution:
According to the standard order of operations, division occurs before subtraction. We find that our answer is \begin{align*}
8-4 \div 2 - 1 &= 8-2-1 \\
&= 6-1 \\
&= \boxed{5}.
\end{align*}

Note that $\dfrac{7}{16}$ and $\dfrac{16}{7}$ are reciprocals. Since $(a \times b)^n = a^n \times b^n$, we get \begin{align*}
\left(\dfrac{7}{16}\right)^{111}\times \left(\dfrac{16}{7}\right)^{111} &= \left(\dfrac{7}{16}\times\dfrac{16}{7}\right)^{111} \\
&= 1^{111} = \boxed{1}.
\end{align*}

The first prime number is $2$ and we know that all prime numbers after that must be odd. $3$, $5$, and $7$ are prime because their only positive integer divisors are $1$ and themselves. $9$ is divisible by $3$ so it is not prime. $11$ and $13$ are prime, but $15$ is not because it is divisible by $3$ and $5$. Continuing, $17$ and $19$ are prime, but $21$ isn't because it is divisible by $3$ and $7$. Finally we know that $23$ is prime.

To sum these nine numbers quicker, we can group them so that they sum to multiples of $10$: \begin{align*}
2+ 3 + 5& + 7 + 11 + 13 + 17 + 19 + 23 \\
& = (3+7) + (11+19) + (13+17) + (23 + 5 + 2) \\
& = 10 + 30 + 30 + 30 \\
& = \boxed{100}
\end{align*}

