Let \[f(x) =
\begin{cases}
5x^2+2&\text{if } x\le a, \\
11x &\text{if } x>a.
\end{cases}
\]Find the smallest possible value for $a$ if the graph of $y=f(x)$ is continuous (which means the graph can be drawn without lifting your pencil from the paper).

ground_truth.solution:
Begin by simplifying the left side: $$3x^2-2x^2-8=42$$ We can combine terms and solve for $x^2$: \begin{align*}
3x^2-2x^2&=42+8\\
\Rightarrow\qquad x^2&=50
\end{align*} Squaring both sides, we find: \begin{align*}
(x^2)^2&=50^2\\
\Rightarrow\qquad x^4&=\boxed{2500}
\end{align*}

The common ratio between consecutive terms is $\frac{6}{4} = \frac{3}{2}$ (we could have chosen any two consecutive terms and divided the second one by the first to find the common ratio; we chose 4 and 6 because they seemed simple). So the $n^\text{th}$ term of the sequence is $\frac{16}{9} \cdot \left( \frac{3}{2} \right)^{n-1}$. Plugging in $n=8$, we get $$
\frac{16}{9} \cdot \left( \frac{3}{2} \right)^{7} = \frac{2^4}{3^2} \cdot \frac{3^7}{2^7}
= \frac{3^5}{2^3}
= \boxed{\frac{243}{8}}.
$$

First we add the two fractions: \begin{align*}
\frac{2}{1 + 2\sqrt{3}} + \frac{3}{2 - \sqrt{3}} & = \frac{2(2-\sqrt{3}) + 3(1 + 2\sqrt{3})}{(1+ 2\sqrt{3})(2 - \sqrt{3})} \\
& = \frac{4\sqrt{3} + 7}{3\sqrt{3}-4}
\end{align*}Now we rationalize the denominator to get the result in the desired form: \begin{align*}
\frac{4\sqrt{3} + 7}{3\sqrt{3}-4} & = \frac{4\sqrt{3} + 7}{3\sqrt{3}-4} \cdot \frac{3\sqrt{3}+4}{3\sqrt{3}+4} \\
& = \frac{(4\sqrt{3} + 7)(3\sqrt{3}+4)}{3^2(3) - 4^2} \\
& = \frac{64 + 37\sqrt{3}}{11}.
\end{align*}This gives $A = 64$, $B = 37$, and $C = 11$, so $A+B+C = \boxed{112}$.

